<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Mount Doom 101<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.81)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=17223'>Joseph "Telcontar" Albers</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=17223&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 22, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont">  This is the first article in a series on the cards of Mount Doom. This first installment will examine the cards of the Dwarven, Elven, and Gandalf cultures, their uses, and possible combos. Anyway, here they are<br />
<br />
Dwarven<br />
<br />
Great Day, Great Hour (3)<br />
Event Response<br />
If an opponent plays a minion, exert a Dwarf who is damage +X to exert that minion X times.<br />
10 R 1<br />
<br />
The latest of the Dwarven Damage cards, GDGH will almost always exhaust the minion that was played for the cost of an exertion. Use this with Greenleaf or Unheeded (or best of all, Quick As May Be) to get the full potential out of this card that works best in a Legolas/Gimli/Power Dwarves deck.<br />
<br />
*Memories of Darkness (1)<br />
Condition Support Area<br />
To play, Spot a Dwarf. Each time you lose initiative (except during the fellowship phase), you may play a [Dwarven] condition from hand or from your discard pile.<br />
10 U 2<br />
<br />
The Dwarven doom of initiative, MoD allows you to cycle discarded conditions from your discard pile whenever you lose initiative outside of the fellowship phase. For Dwarves, regaining your Preperations or Aggressions has never been easier. With the cycling power of the Dwarves, losing initiative is simple. Just beware the consequences of giving initiative to the wrong shadow side! MoD works in any Dwarven conditions deck.<br />
<br />
More Yet To Come (0)<br />
Event Response<br />
If a Dwarf kills a minion in a skirmish and that minion did not take all wounds caused by that Dwarf&#39;s damage bonus, assign those remaining wounds to minions not assigned to a skirmish.<br />
10 R 3<br />
<br />
At first glance MYtC is one of the most awesome Dwarven cards yet, but a second look will cool that excitement. MYtC only wounds minions that have already skirmished or did not skirmish. Sure, you can use it with your damage+10 Dwarf to clear out all minions, but this is difficult to pull off and your Dwarves should be killing off everything anyway. Not bad, but not worth running more than 1 in your Power Dwarves deck.<br />
<br />
Elven<br />
<br />
*Aegnor, Elven Escort (2)<br />
Companion Elf<br />
Strength 6 Vitality 3 Signet: None<br />
Skirmish: Exert Aegnor to make a minion skirmishing an unbound [Elven] companion strength -1 for each archer you spot.<br />
10 U 4<br />
<br />
Finally &quot;Figwit&quot; is revealed! Aegnor is an interesting companion who probably will not see much play. His ability could come in handy in an Elven Telepathy deck, but with Galadriel, MoW, Glorfindel, Legolas, Arwen, Gil-Galad, and the possible Naith Troop it will be hard to find a place for the Elven Escort. Could possibly find room in a Last Alliance Deck w/Aragorn&#39;s Bow and Faramir&#39;s Bow.<br />
<br />
*Arwen, Echo of Luthien (2)<br />
Companion Elf<br />
Strength 6 Vitality 3 Signet: Aragorn<br />
Skirmish: Discard a card from hand to discard the bottom card of your draw deck. If the bottom card was an [Elven] card, each minion skirmishing Arwen is strength -3.<br />
10 U 5<br />
<br />
Beren and Luthien telepathy decks may now be viable! EoL will be a fixture along with Glorfindel, RiW and Still Needed/Fleet-Footed. With Into the West [Elven] cards on top of your deck can be moved to the bottom for use with Arwen and Beren and Luthien. For another cool combo, Use Old Noser to wound minions for a double move while setting up the bottom of your deck for telepathy. Include 2-3 copies of Elrond, VL for best results in your telepathy deck.<br />
<br />
*Arwen, Queen of Elves and Men (2)<br />
Companion Elf<br />
Strength 6 Vitality 3 Signet: Frodo<br />
Each minion skirmishing Arwen is strength -2 for each wounded minion you can spot.<br />
10 R 6<br />
<br />
The new powerhouse for Last Alliance or other archery decks, QoEaM will see plenty of play and may make Legolas, ES usable. With Gwemegil and the new Asfaloth, QoEaM will be a killing machine. Use Feathered in her skirmish and start overwhelming Balrogs and Trolls! This Arwen is possibly the best companion in the set.<br />
<br />
*Celeborn, Lord of the Galadhrim (2)<br />
Companion Elf<br />
Strength 6 Vitality 3 Signet: None<br />
At the start of each skirmish involving Celeborn, you may reveal the top card of your draw deck. If it is an [Elven] card, you may discard it to wound each minion in that skirmish.<br />
10 R 7<br />
<br />
One of the two &quot;Revealers&quot; in Mount Doom, Celeborn gives you the option of discarding the revealed card to wound all minions skirmishing him. This will only help on rare occasions as most 1 vitality minions pose no problem for the Lord of the Galadhrim anyway. His best use is simply to reveal the top card of your draw deck for Telepathy decks. Not bad, but not good enough to merit his rare status as he will only fit into Beren and Luthien telepathy decks due to the lack of other possible companions.<br />
<br />
*Cirdan, The Shipwright (4)<br />
Companion Elf<br />
Strength 7 Vitality 4 Signet: None<br />
To play, spot 2 Elves. Skirmish: Exert Cirdan to make a minion he is skirmishing strength -1 for each [Elven] event in your discard pile.<br />
10 R 8<br />
<br />
Wow, this guy&#39;s a beast! Fighting Elves anyone? Now you can find a use for all of your Valors and Defiances. Run three of Cirdan and use your events freely. Throw in Bow of the Galadhrim, Gift of Galadriel and Hope Comes for best results. Also makes an incredibly potent combo with Galadriel, Lady Redeemed. The Shipwright can even bear Narya, Ring of Fire to counter Corsairs and other specialized shadows. Cirdan will possibly revitalize the forgotten archery and Naith decks of the Fellowship/Two Towers days.<br />
<br />
*Elrond, Venerable Lord (4)<br />
Companion Elf<br />
Strength 8 Vitality 4 Signet: None<br />
To play, spot an Elf. At the start of each skirmish involving Elrond, you may reveal the top card of your draw deck. If it is an [Elven] card, you may heal another Elf.<br />
10 R 9<br />
<br />
The second of the &quot;Revealers&quot; is by far the best. Venerable Lord completely dwarfs the Elven Lord and is even powerful enough to find a spot in most Telepathy decks. His ability to heal w/out discarding the revealed card leaves Celeborn in the dust. He will even work well in a BaL deck with Arwen, EoL. Here I will take the time to say that the Elves are the most improved culture (with the possible exception of the Shire) in Mount Doom by far.<br />
<br />
Fleet-Footed (1)<br />
Event Skirmish<br />
Make a minion skirmishing an Elf strength -2. Spot a site in a support area to place this event on top of your draw deck.<br />
10 C 10<br />
<br />
This is basically Still Needed with an extra condition. Sure it gives -2 strength rather than +2, but this is only ever more useful when overwhelming minions, which Elves do not need much help doing anyway with Feathered and Blades Drawn. Only possible use is as extra Still Neededs that only give full satisfaction if you&#39;re playing site control. I&#39;ll take Still Needed any day.<br />
<br />
*Galadriel, Lady Redeemed (3)<br />
Companion Elf<br />
Strength 3 Vitality 3 Signet: None<br />
When Galadriel is in your starting fellowship, her twilight cost is -3. Fellowship or Regroup: Discard an [Elven] event from hand to discard a Shadow condition or Shadow Possession.<br />
10 R 11<br />
<br />
Who needs Roll of Thunder? The Lady Redeemed is now the easiest, most powerful condition AND possession removal period. You can even start her for free! If nothing else, she serves as a chump blocker. Is Grond giving you problems? Simply wait for them to build up enough tokens and then pitch an event and watch the look on your opponent&#39;s face. Galadriel, LR can fit into both fighting Naith decks, archery decks, and telepathy decks as well as just about every other deck that uses [Elven] Events. Her only downside is that you have to choose between her and Bearer of Wisdom in your deck. Oh well, life isn&#39;t perfect (Sigh...).<br />
<br />
*Glimpse of Fate (0)<br />
Condition Support Area<br />
To play, spot 2 Elves. Each time you lose initiative, make a minion strength -4 until the regroup phase.<br />
10 U 12<br />
<br />
The Elven doom of initiative, GoF can tone down that Sauron, or Cave Troll for you throughout their fierce skirmishes. You can even use Hope Comes and Elven Swords for a wacky combo that can allow you to re-use GoF on the same minion! GoF is one of the better doom of initiative cards.<br />
<br />
*Phial of Galadriel, Star-Glass (0)<br />
Artifact<br />
Bearer must be a Hobbit. Skirmish: Until the regroup phase, remove the game text (except card type and race) from a minion skirmishing bearer and make it unable to gain game text. Discard this artifact.<br />
10 R 13<br />
<br />
The new Phial is quite a bit more interesting than the old one. Rather than a bland +2 resistance, you get to remove a minion&#39;s game text. Worried about Enduring, Damage +1, +2? The Star-Glass removes all of that plus all other text. Do you fall victim to the A Dark Shape Sprang w/Old Villain? Fear not, just equip your ring-bearer with this artifact and Gollum is reduced to an ordinary 5 strength minion who will pose no problem to you. This one doesn&#39;t even have any spot requirements. Star-Glass works well in any deck that uses Frodo or Bilbo as its ring-bearer.<br />
<br />
Borne Far Away (1)<br />
Event Fellowship<br />
Spot your Wizard to exchange a companion in hand with a companion in your dead pile or discard pile.<br />
10 R 14<br />
<br />
This culture is crazy! In Siege of Gondor, Gandalf got Saved From the Fire to put people in your dead pile and now you can exchange them too. Remember losing your Aragorn to an ill-timed Red Wrath or Relentless Charge? Just play with Gandalf and have your Oathbreaker take his place (after all he&#39;s already dead anyway). BFA is also protection against Fierce in Despair. You can even use this with Saved From the Fire and begin to manipulate the dead pile! BFA works in any deck with Gandalf. Still would have preferred Eagle companions though (maybe in Shadows).<br />
<br />
*Brooding On Tomorrow (1)<br />
Condition Support Area<br />
Each time you lose initiative (except during the fellowship phase), you may spot a [Gandalf] companion to choose an opponent who must discard one of his or her conditions.<br />
10 U 15<br />
<br />
The Gandalf doom of initiative card, this allows you to do one of the things Gandalf does best, discard conditions. This will probably work best in an Ent deck that uses the unhasty Ents to discard and lose initiative. Might also work in an event-heavy Gandalf deck, but it probably won’t be needed.<br />
<br />
Gathering Wind (2)<br />
Event Maneuver<br />
Exert your Wizard and choose a number. Make each minion with that twilight cost strength –2 until the regroup phase.<br />
10 C 16<br />
<br />
This card is not that good. It was meant to counter swarms and it will occasionally work, but I’ll take Wielder of the Flame any day. May be splashed into miscellaneous Gandalf decks.<br />
<br />
Our of the High Airs (3)<br />
Event Response<br />
If the fellowship moves during the regroup phase, exert your Wizard to discard each minion.<br />
10 R 17<br />
<br />
This may be the best regroup event in the game! I can envision Orc Ambushers seeing play just to prevent this. OotHA  will see play in every deck that uses Gandalf at all. This card is all but broken.<br />
<br />
*Treebeard, Keeper of the Watchwood (5)<br />
Companion Ent<br />
Strength 12 Vitality 4 Signet: None<br />
To play, spot 3 [Gandalf] companions. Regroup: Exert Treebeard to play a [Gandalf] condition from your discard pile and make an opponent discard one of his or her conditions.<br />
<br />
Can you say Entish Galadriel? Treebeard, KotW is an exceptional character with one drawback: He needs 3 other Ents/Gandalf to play. If you get this guy out early with an Ent Draught, Moria and Besiegers won’t know what hit them. As for Shelob, well, it’s a good thing she never met an Ent! In addition to all of this you get to retrieve your lost conditions. The only hesitation I may have is whether to play this guy or Guardian of the Forest.<br />
<br />
Well, that wraps up my first article. Here I will say that with the possible exception of Reflections, Mount Doom features the most powerful arsenal of companions in my opinion. Hope I haven’t put you to sleep by now. Next time I will explore the remaining Free Peoples cultures: Gondor, Rohan, and Shire. Until then!<br />
<br />
Telcontar<br />
“In the high tongue it will not sound so ill”<br />
